t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="contentSub"></div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">\n\t\t\t\t\tJump to:\t\t\t\t\t<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, \t\t\t\t\t<a href="#p-search">search</a>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div id="portals-browsebar" class="hlist" style="text-align: center;">\n<dl>\n<dt><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Topics</a></dt>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Culture_and_the_arts" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Culture</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Geography_and_places" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Geography</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Health_and_fitness" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Health</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#History_and_events" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">History</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Mathematics_and_logic" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Mathematics</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Natural_and_physical_sciences" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Nature</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#People_and_self" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">People</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Philosophy_and_thinking" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Philosophy</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Religion_and_belief_systems" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Religion</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Society_and_social_sciences" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Society</a></dd>\n<dd><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals#Technology_and_applied_sciences" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">Technology</a></dd>\n</dl>\n</div>\n<div style="clear:both; width:100%">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Intro&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Children.27s_Literature_Portal"><big>The Children\'s Literature Portal</big></span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:right;margin-left:1em">\n<center><a href="/wiki/Reading_education" class="mw-redirect" title="Reading education">Reading education</a></center>\n<p><a href="/wiki/File:Family_Reading_Hour.jpg" class="image" title="By flickr user Peter Merholz"><img alt="By flickr user Peter Merholz" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Family_Reading_Hour.jpg/200px-Family_Reading_Hour.jpg" width="200" height="142" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Family_Reading_Hour.jpg/300px-Family_Reading_Hour.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Family_Reading_Hour.jpg/400px-Family_Reading_Hour.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2244" data-file-height="1588" /></a><br /></p>\n</div>\n<p><b><a href="/wiki/Children%27s_literature" title="Children\'s literature">Children\'s literature</a></b> is literature written for and/or marketed towards a primarily juvenile audience. While some books are authored for a youthful audience, others become associated with children through marketing or tradition. Still others are "crossover" books, read by children and adults alike. Literature addressed directly to children arose in Western Europe in the late 17th and early 18th centuries, becoming a very profitable industry in the 19th century. It includes <a href="/wiki/Picture_books" class="mw-redirect" title="Picture books">picture books</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fairy_tale" title="Fairy tale">fairy tales</a>, <a href="/wiki/Animal_Stories" title="Animal Stories">animal stories</a>, <a href="/wiki/School_story" title="School story">school stories</a>, <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fantasy" title="Fantasy">fantasy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Book_series" title="Book series">series fiction</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chapter_book" title="Chapter book">chapter books</a>, <a href="/wiki/Children%27s_poetry" title="Children\'s poetry">children\'s poetry</a>, and other genres. Throughout its 300-year history, children\'s stories have reflected the values of the societies that produced them.</p>\n<table width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin:0; background:transparent;">\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:-4px;"><b><a href="/wiki/Children%27s_literature" title="Children\'s literature">More about children\'s literature...</a></b></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="text-align:center; margin:0.25em auto 0.75em"><span class="noprint plainlinks purgelink"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature&amp;action=purge"><span title="Purge this page"><b>Show new selections</b></span></a></span></div>\n</div>\n<div class="portal-column-left-wide">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_article/17&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_article">Selected article</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:left;margin-right:1em"><a href="/wiki/File:Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Gustave Dore le chat botte.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg/100px-Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg" width="100" height="132" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg/150px-Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg/200px-Gustave_Dore_le_chat_botte.jpg 2x" data-file-width="316" data-file-height="416" /></a></div>\n"<b><a href="/wiki/Puss_in_Boots" title="Puss in Boots">Puss in Boots</a></b>" is a French literary <a href="/wiki/Fairy_tale" title="Fairy tale">fairy tale</a> about a cat who uses trickery and deceit to gain power, wealth, and the hand of a princess in marriage for his penniless and low-born master. The tale was written at the close of the seventeenth century by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Perrault" title="Charles Perrault">Charles Perrault</a>, a retired civil servant and member of the <i><a href="/wiki/Acad%C3%A9mie_fran%C3%A7aise" title="Acad\xc3\xa9mie fran\xc3\xa7aise">Acad\xc3\xa9mie fran\xc3\xa7aise</a></i>. The book was an instant success and remains popular today. The tale\'s immorality has provoked some concern about its influence on young minds, but Perrault composed "Le Maistre Chat" and the other tales of <i>Histoires</i> to reinforce standards of civilized conduct in the upper-class French society of the seventeenth century rather than to provide amusement and instruction for the young. Indeed, Puss has been described by one commentator as "the epitome of the educated bourgeois secretary who serves his master with complete devotion and diligence." Perrault\'s <i>Histoires</i> has had considerable impact on world culture. The <a href="/wiki/Book_frontispiece" title="Book frontispiece">frontispiece</a> to the earliest English editions depicts an old woman telling tales to a group of children beneath a placard inscribed \'MOTHER GOOSE\'S TALES\' and is credited with launching the <a href="/wiki/Mother_Goose" title="Mother Goose">Mother Goose</a> legend in the English-speaking world.\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:left;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_article" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/Selected article">...Archive/Nominations</a></b></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;">\n<p><b><a href="/wiki/Puss_in_Boots" title="Puss in Boots">More...</a></b></p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_picture/21&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_picture">Selected picture</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="center">\n<div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg" class="image" title="Benjamin and Flopsy Bunny - Beatrix Potter characters"><img alt="Benjamin and Flopsy Bunny - Beatrix Potter characters" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg/250px-Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg" width="250" height="283" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg/375px-Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg/500px-Benjamin_and_Flopsy_Bunny_-_Project_Gutenberg_eText_14220.jpg 2x" data-file-width="831" data-file-height="940" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td width="33%">\n<center><small>Credit: <a href="/wiki/Beatrix_Potter" title="Beatrix Potter">Beatrix Potter</a></small></center>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<p>Benjamin, Flopsaut and the little rabbits from <i>The Tale of The Flopsy Bunnies</i>, original version written and illustrated by <a href="/wiki/Beatrix_Potter" title="Beatrix Potter">Beatrix Potter</a></p>\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td width="33%">\n<div style="text-align:left;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_picture" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/Selected picture">...Archive/Nominations</a></b></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;">\n<p><b><a href="/wiki/The_Tale_of_The_Flopsy_Bunnies" class="mw-redirect" title="The Tale of The Flopsy Bunnies">More...</a></b></p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_anniversaries/August&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="In_this_month">In this month</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:right;margin-left:0.5em;">\n<p><a href="/wiki/File:Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg" class="image" title="Janusz Korczak memorial"><img alt="Janusz Korczak memorial" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg/100px-Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg/150px-Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg/200px-Israel-Yad_Vashem_Janus_Korczak_children_memorial.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600" /></a></p>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li>August 1942 - Death of <b><a href="/wiki/Janusz_Korczak" title="Janusz Korczak">Janusz Korczak</a></b>, <i>(memorial pictured)</i>, a <a href="/wiki/Polish-Jewish" class="mw-redirect" title="Polish-Jewish">Polish-Jewish</a> <a href="/wiki/Children%27s_literature" title="Children\'s literature">children\'s author</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pediatrics" title="Pediatrics">pediatrician</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Pedagogy" title="Pedagogy">pedagogue</a></li>\n<li>August 2007 \xe2\x80\x93 <b><a href="/wiki/Lloyd_Alexander" title="Lloyd Alexander">Lloyd Alexander</a></b>, known for his <i><a href="/wiki/The_Chronicles_of_Prydain" title="The Chronicles of Prydain">Chronicles of Prydain</a></i>, publishes his last novel</li>\n<li>August 2007 \xe2\x80\x93 <i><b><a href="/wiki/The_Dandy" title="The Dandy">The Dandy</a></b></i>, the third-longest running comic in the world, becomes <i>The Dandy Xtreme</i></li>\n<li>11 August 1897 \xe2\x80\x93 Birth of <b><a href="/wiki/Enid_Blyton" title="Enid Blyton">Enid Blyton</a></b>, the fifth-most translated author worldwide</li>\n<li>28 August 1995 \xe2\x80\x93 Death of <b><a href="/wiki/Michael_Ende" title="Michael Ende">Michael Ende</a></b>, German children\'s writer best known for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Neverending_Story" title="The Neverending Story">The Neverending Story</a></i></li>\n</ul>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_anniversaries" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/Selected anniversaries">More anniversaries...</a></b></div>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_quote/19&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_quote">Selected quote</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<center>\n<table class="noprint" border="0" style="text-align:left; padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td><i>JOHN: How do you do it [fly]?<br />\nPETER: You just think lovely wonderful thoughts and they lift you up in the air.</i>\n<div style="text-align:right; margin-right:10px">\xe2\x80\x94 <b><a href="/wiki/J._M._Barrie" title="J. M. Barrie">J. M. Barrie</a></b>, <i><a href="/wiki/Peter_Pan" title="Peter Pan">Peter Pan</a></i></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</center>\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:left;margin-bottom:0px;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_quote" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/Selected quote">...Archive/Nominations</a></b></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:0px;"><b><a href="https://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Literature" class="extiw" title="wikiquote:Literature">More...</a></b></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class="portal-column-right-narrow">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_biography/11&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_biography">Selected biography</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:right;margin-left:0.2em"><a href="/wiki/File:Christopher_Smart.jpg" class="image" title="Christopher Smart"><img alt="Christopher Smart" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Christopher_Smart.jpg/115px-Christopher_Smart.jpg" width="115" height="143" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Christopher_Smart.jpg/173px-Christopher_Smart.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Christopher_Smart.jpg/230px-Christopher_Smart.jpg 2x" data-file-width="241" data-file-height="300" /></a></div>\n<b><a href="/wiki/Christopher_Smart" title="Christopher Smart">Christopher Smart</a></b> (11 April 1722 \xe2\x80\x93 21 May 1771) was an <a href="/wiki/English_people" title="English people">English</a> poet. He was a major contributor to two popular magazines and a friend to influential cultural icons like <a href="/wiki/Samuel_Johnson" title="Samuel Johnson">Samuel Johnson</a> and <a href="/wiki/Henry_Fielding" title="Henry Fielding">Henry Fielding</a>. Smart, a <a href="/wiki/High_church" title="High church">high church</a> <a href="/wiki/Anglican" class="mw-redirect" title="Anglican">Anglican</a>, was widely known throughout London. Smart was infamous for his role as "Mrs. Mary Midnight" and widespread accounts of his father-in-law, <a href="/wiki/John_Newbery" title="John Newbery">John Newbery</a>, locking him away in a <a href="/wiki/Psychiatric_hospital" title="Psychiatric hospital">mental asylum</a> for many years over Smart\'s supposed religious "mania". Even after Smart\'s eventual release, a negative reputation continued to pursue him as he was known for incurring more debt than he could pay off; this ultimately led to his confinement in debtor\'s prison until his death. Smart\'s two most widely-known works are <i><a href="/wiki/A_Song_to_David" title="A Song to David">A Song to David</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Jubilate_Agno" title="Jubilate Agno">Jubilate Agno</a></i>, both at least partly written during his confinement in asylum. However, <i>Jubilate Agno</i> was not to be published until 1939 and <i>A Song to David</i> received mixed reviews until the 19th century. To his contemporaries, Smart was known mainly for his many contributions in the journals <i>The Midwife</i> and <i>The Student</i>, along with his famous <i>Seaton Prize poems</i> and his mock epic <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hilliad" title="The Hilliad">The Hilliad</a></i>. Although he is primarily recognized as a religious poet, his poetry includes various other themes, such as his theories on nature and his promotion of English nationalism. Some of his most famous religious poetry is <i><a href="/wiki/Hymns_for_the_Amusement_of_Children" title="Hymns for the Amusement of Children">Hymns for the Amusement of Children</a></i>, one of the first books of hymns expressly written for a juvenile audience.\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:left;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/Selected_biography" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/Selected biography">...Archive/Nominations</a></b></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;">\n<p><b><a href="/wiki/Christopher_Smart" title="Christopher Smart">More...</a></b></p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/DYK/15&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Did_you_know...">Did you know...</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:right;margin-left:0.5em;">\n<p><a href="/wiki/File:Map_of_USA_LA.svg" class="image" title="Louisiana"><img alt="Louisiana" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Map_of_USA_LA.svg/100px-Map_of_USA_LA.svg.png" width="100" height="65" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Map_of_USA_LA.svg/150px-Map_of_USA_LA.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Map_of_USA_LA.svg/200px-Map_of_USA_LA.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="286" data-file-height="186" /></a></p>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li>...that <i><b><a href="/wiki/Polycarp_(children%27s_TV_show_host)" title="Polycarp (children\'s TV show host)">Polycarp</a></b></i> was a fictional <a href="/wiki/Cajun" class="mw-redirect" title="Cajun">Cajun</a> character who hosted a local children\'s TV program in <a href="/wiki/South_Louisiana" class="mw-redirect" title="South Louisiana">south Louisiana</a> <i>(Louisiana pictured)</i> and lived in the <a href="/wiki/Swamp" title="Swamp">swamp</a>?</li>\n<li>...that <a href="/wiki/Norwegians" title="Norwegians">Norwegian</a> researchers published <i><b><a href="/wiki/Gay_Kids" title="Gay Kids">Gay Kids</a></b></i> in November 2008 to educate children about <a href="/wiki/Homosexual" class="mw-redirect" title="Homosexual">homosexual</a> love?</li>\n<li>...that according to <i><b><a href="/wiki/Street_Gang_(book)" class="mw-redirect" title="Street Gang (book)">Street Gang</a></b></i>, a discussion at a dinner party, hosted by <a href="/wiki/Joan_Ganz_Cooney" title="Joan Ganz Cooney">Joan Ganz Cooney</a> in 1966, led to the creation of the children\'s television show, <i><a href="/wiki/Sesame_Street" title="Sesame Street">Sesame Street</a></i>?</li>\n</ul>\n<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:left;margin-bottom:0px;"><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature/DYK" title="Portal:Children\'s literature/DYK">...Archive/Nominations</a></b></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:0px;">\n<p><b><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Recent_additions" title="Wikipedia:Recent additions">More...</a></b></p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #567364; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #82D9AD; color: black; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: black"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Children%27s_literature/Projects&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: black">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:black;"><span class="mw-headline" id="WikiProjects">WikiProjects</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #567364; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: F5FFFA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div style="float:right;margin-left:0.9em"><a href="/wiki/File:Community.png" class="image" title="WikiProjects"><img alt="WikiProjects" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/ce/Community.png" width="50" height="33" data-file-width="48" data-file-height="32" /></a></div>\n<dl>\n<dt>Parent projects</dt>\n</dl>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Literature" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Literature">Literature</a>&#160;\xe2\x80\xa2  <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Books">Books</a>&#160;\xe2\x80\xa2  <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels">Novels</a></li>\n</ul>\n<dl>\n<dt>Main project</dt>\n</dl>\n<ul>\n<li><b><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Children%27s_literature" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Children\'s literature">Wikipedia:WikiProject Children\'s literature</a></b></li>\n</ul>\n<dl>\n<dt>Related projects</d